You can add your voice to the tens of thousands of comments posted daily on Express.co.uk and have your say on the big issues facing the country today. Government figures for 2019 show Pakistan was the top recipient of that year for bilateral aid - £305 million - and has received the most from the UK for some years now. Despite expressing concern about the fallout from the Russian invasion of Ukraine, the South Asian nation has stopped short of condemning it. Last week, Pakistan also provisionally contracted Moscow to build a lucrative natural gas pipeline to run through the country with Prime Minister Imran Khan flying to Russia for a meeting with Vladimir Putin.   The project was estimated to cost about $2.5 billion (£2.1 billion) with Russia benefiting significantly. However, the war in Ukraine has triggered a mounting humanitarian crisis in Europe and raised the prospect of nuclear conflict. So, should the UK divert its foreign aid to Pakistan and instead send it to Ukraine? Or should it be spent on strengthening the UK’s military at a time of crisis? HAVE YOUR SAY RIGHT NOW - JOIN THE EXPRESS READER DEBATE IN OUR COMMENTS SECTION. 